results.notes:
Collected by an unknown participant of the NJMA foray. Grayish-beige caps; photo colors accurate.
DNA Sequencing Results & Discussion (posted 15-May-21):
> A clean and contiguous full-length nrITS sequence of 468 base pairs (bps) was obtained from this material by Dr. Kudzma. The ITS1 and ITS2 subloci are 160 and 148 bps long, respectively, while the 5.8S region is of the standard 160 bps length in this species/organism. The the forward and reverse reads are stitched together at a single point of heterogeneity in a poly-“TA” repeat at the very end of the ITS1 region; hence, it’s not a consensus sequence, but a “joined contig”. The sequence is preceded by the last 19 characters of nrSSU at its 5’ end and followed by the first 65 bps of nrLSU at its 3’ end. There are no ambiguities in the final sequence.
> According to Rod Tulloss (RET), the ITS sequence matched Amanita longicuneoides in his private DNA database (8-Mar-21 personal communication). RET hasn’t published nrDNA data for this species in GenBank yet. For further info, see http://amanitaceae.org/?Amanita%20longicuneoides. This taxon was formerly called ‘Amanita sp-longicuneus03’ in RET’s website.
> Based on the BLASTn-100 search, the ITS sequence of A. longicuneoides is structurally most similar to accessions of Amanita salmonriverensis (still labeled as ‘Amanita sp-longicuneus02’ in GenBank), also so far known only from New Jersey: http://amanitaceae.org/?Amanita%20salmonriverensis.
> Alignment of the ITS sequences of A. longicuneoides and A. salmonriverensis (MK569746 & MK569747) are shown in Fig. 1. The two salmonriverensis accessions differ from each other only at characters #71 (in ITS1) and #297 (in 5.8S), both of which appear to be pyrimidine-type single nucleotide polymorphisms.

results.notes:
This observation is the culmination of several days of following the progress of this mushroom species in my home yard. When I first noticed this entity I only saw an oddly formed pileus with strong sinuses and upturned margins, which showed the gills from the side.

I got very interested in this particular mushroom due to its atypicality. I’ve been visiting the spot in my lawn where I’ve seen the most numbers of individuals. Today I noticed some individuals that did not have the atypical look described above. Rather there were now some which showed a typical rounded cap with the gills not conspicuous.

I began to realize that these new forms were the same species as the one I’d been monitoring, mainly due to the color (a very light “beige”, almost off-white), the identical gills on both types, and as is shown in some images, the fact that both forms/types are growing together in one area.

See individual photos which have descriptive captions.

Now I’d like to find out what this mushroom species is! It’s really captivated me as a new student of mushroomery!
